inished popular reliance on the religious “cure of the soul,” and witnessed the emergence of psychoanalysis. From its inception, Freud’s psychoanalysis was accused of being a “Jewish science,” and he countered by including non-Jewish Swiss psychiatrists in his movement. Carl Jung eventually broke with Freud due to differences concerning psychoanalytical theory and practice. This text explores the religious underpinnings of psychoanalysis, contrasting the textual and mystical traditions of Judaism with those of Christianity. It convincingly demonstrates that differences in the fundamental tenets of Judaism and Christianity have had a profound and continued influence on psychoanalysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChristianityxPsychological aspects. 0aPsychoanalysis and religion. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015z97831110235570 cprintz978161811422840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161811423540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618114235423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618114235/original  a978-3-11-068814-6  Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  a978-3-11-102355-7  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK